A: This should work for you: a = "hello world" b=[] c=a.split() # Split the string into list (TO minimize number of loops) and iterate to # append " " and "\n" to each list item. for d in c: e=d+"\n" b.append(e) print(b) Common one liner (simpler version) : b = [d + "\n"for d in a.split()] Output: ['hello\n', 'world\n']

In your question, you are trying to append a string to the string such as i=' hello' Now, you are appending '\n' to ' hello' to the third element of the list. This must throw you an error.
